  "prompt": "How common is using \"ex\" as the short for \"example\"?",
  "response": "Using \"ex\" as a short form for \"example\" is relatively common, particularly in informal contexts such as notes, texts, or casual communication. However, in formal writing, it is more standard to use \"e.g.\" (from the Latin \"exempli gratia\") to indicate an example. The use of \"ex\" can sometimes lead to confusion because it is also a common abbreviation for \"exercise\" or \"excluding,\" depending on the context. Therefore, while \"ex\" is understood by many as a shorthand for \"example,\" it is generally advisable to use \"e.g.\" in more formal settings to avoid ambiguity.",
